tervention from Ottawa, the provinces have fashioned what amounts to a de facto pan-Canadian system.Learning to School explains how and why the provinces have achieved this unexpected result. Beginning with the earliest provincial education policies and taking readers right up to contemporary policy debates, the book chronicles how, through learning and cooperation, the provinces gradually established a country-wide system of public schooling. A rich and ambitious work of scholarship, it will appeal to readers seeking fresh insights on Canadian federalism, education policy, and policy diffusion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aEducation and statezCanadaxHistory. 0aEducation and statezCanada. 0aPublic schoolszCanadaxHistory. 0aPublic schoolszCanada. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Canadian.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Pilot 2014-2015z978311060681240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266928440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442669284423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442669284.jpg  a978-3-11-060681-2  University of Toronto Press Pilot 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK